#A balance dataset is important because it help with a greater accuracy. For example if, we work on a dataset with 90% tall
#and 10% short, when we test it on some other data, it might not have the right predictions

#The are a couple of ways to deal with imbalance dataset
#One way is to check is we can get more data,
#Another way is under-sampling, oversampling, and  generating synthetic data

#LabelEncoder encode labels with a value between 0 and n_classes-1 
#where n is the number of distinct labels. 
#For example if we have a column = [dog,cats,rats,dogs], Label encoder would be [0,1,2,0]

#One hot encoding takes a column which has categorical data and splits the column into multiple columns. 
#The numbers are replaced by 1s and 0s, depending on which column has what value. 
#For example the column above will be splilt into 3 different coloumns

#We should use one hot encoding When the categorical feature is not ordinal (dog, cat, rat)

#We should use label encoding The categorical feature is ordinal
#When we can come up with a label encoder that assigns close labels to similar categories
In [28]:
#Multicollinearity occurs in our dataset when we have features which are strongly dependent on each other
#We care about multicollinearity because if we have multicollinearity in our dataset then we wont be able to use our weight vector to calculate the feature importance.
#Multicollinearity impacts the interpretability of our model
In [29]:
#The easiest method to identify Multicollinearity is to just plot a pairplot
#We can also use heatmap to tell if out dataset has multicollinearity
In [30]:
#scaling is important because if not scale, some features with a higher value range starts dominating when calculating distances
In [31]:
#logistic regression model is parametric because it has a finite set of parameters
#KNN , svm are a non parametric algorithm

#Aparametricalgorithm has afixed number of parameters.
#A parametric algorithm iscomputationally faster, but makesstronger assumptionsabout the data
#While non-parametricalgorithm uses aflexible number of parameters, and the number of parameters 
#oftengrows as it learns from more data. A non-parametric algorithm iscomputationally slower, 
#but makesfewer assumptionsabout the data
